This belief differs from the primary concern couples have about the status of the foetus, where 76% stated life began between conception and birth (including 48% who stated life began at conception). Just over half the sample (52%) said they would not donate body parts, blood or participate in medical experiments. This implies that the majority of the Bates and Simmons (1998) sample would not donate organs even in situations when organ donation would be very beneficial, such as when it could prolong the life of the next of kin.

The majority of Bates and Simmons’ (1998) respondents viewed abortion as ‘murder’ (57%), ‘an opinion’ of the person’s faith/morality (43%) or ‘child abuse’ (20%).
